          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between an internal audit and a tax audit?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Internal audit is a management driven review of controls and processes, carried out as often as the board decides and with no prescribed format. A tax audit is a statutory income tax requirement under Section 44AB, reported in Form 3CA or 3CB along with Form 3CD, and applies once turnover crosses the prescribed limit."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can only a chartered accountant be appointed as a statutory auditor?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. Section 141 of the Companies Act 2013 allows only a chartered accountant in practice, or a firm where the majority of partners practising in India are chartered accountants, to be appointed statutory auditor. Internal audit is wider: Section 138 permits a chartered accountant, a cost accountant or any other professional the board decides, including an employee."
